AA53FFA7E145422EB515C2B4F4B20477.description: Use some conventional letters in their writing.

45045BF4B186484AAC10A2555E64BB83.description:
Imitate adult writing
conventions that they have
observed (write groups of
letter-like forms separated
by spaces, try to write on
a line, press Enter key on
computer after typing a series
of “words”).

2666AA9DEC04454C8094D40C4D9FDD22.description:
Use a variety of writing tools
and materials with increasing
precision.

AA942DB97988474AA5D10871412AFD4A.description:
Play with writing letters and make
letter-like forms.

6778BF43B96F400C9B50E3D518618FAF.description:
Make marks they call “writing”
that look different from drawings (vertical series of marks for a
“grocery list,” horizontal line of
marks for a “story”).

860D0BB622BF422E9612CEAD60059334.description:
Use a variety of writing tools and
materials with purpose and control
(pencils, chalk, markers, crayons, paintbrushes, finger paint,
computers).

D58F978214A149A98D203BC16A51C2FC.description:
Transition from
holding a crayon or
marker in their fist to holding it between
thumb and forefinger.

9E9A96CDDE9F4869BD34990013EA94C0.description:
Scribble and/or
imitate an adult’s marks with markers, crayons,
paints, etc.

907E34674550430AA1B044D51AB4588D.description:
Explore a variety of
tools that can be used
for writing.

286692937C1640549EDD5ED9BD9630D7.description:
Dot or scribble
with crayons, may
progress to
vertical lines.

BAB454CB134E4671952BEBAF89D50732.description:
Hold marker or
crayon with their
fist.

0F66C27B30264B638A2C5617B27E0A59.description: Children use writing skills and conventions.

09C4C5A351A14F5E9B36C12B03EAE372.description:
Try to connect the sounds in
a spoken word with letters in
the written word (write “M” and
say, “This is Mommy.”).

DC58C4615B2C41B184EF659644BA52B1.description:
Use known letters and approximations of letters to write
their own name and some
familiar words.

9A12DDBF1D364EFFA9F725FF720F86D4.description:
Show they know that written
words are made up of particular
letters (point to the first letter
of their own name, find the first
letter of their own name in a list of
letters).

226CFBA720F3439F9514E28F846B670F.description:
Distinguish letters from different
kinds of drawings/graphics.

92BAECAFA27E48FC98D4D1559EEA7C27.description:
Begin to use letters and
approximations of letters to write
their name.

EDA612815C034221BE079DEA655B7A66.description: Children use knowledge of letters in their attempts to write.

87021B0A94D5442683656BC6850BA62A.description:
Engage in discussions regarding
different purposes (enjoyment,
information) and forms of writing
(narrative, informational, and
opinion).

76A1F779351C4139AC79BB700BAFAA98.description:
Independently engage in writing
behaviors for various purposes
(e.g., write symbols or letters for
names, use materials at writing
center, write lists with symbols/
letters in pretend play, write
messages that include letters or
symbols).

E87F40777EBB4376888051EE4716C272.description:
Communicate their thoughts for
an adult to write.

D0288162DFC94DCCBBA3234459930DFF.description:
Incorporate representations of
signs, logos, or other commonly
used symbols into their drawing
or writing to communicate the
messages that they convey.

C536C5BA9F704ECE93B82BF643218C69.description:
Represent thoughts and ideas in
drawings and by writing letters or
letter-like forms.

04F07FF521A547FBA674682532159217.description:
Engage in writing
behaviors that imitate
real-life situations
(e.g., make marks to
take food order during
pretend restaurant play).

14235C5D134F4FC4B3C64F8FFEBA8F06.description:
With prompting and
support, communicate
their thoughts for an
adult to write.

3471F633882E4A13B4F894DE1DD41480.description:
Represent thoughts
and ideas through
marks, scribbles,
drawings, and paintings
(draw a picture of
something they did
during the day, indicate
what they want for lunch
with a mark under the
picture of the food they
want).

434D446D5EE14CAC93DB5C28F08C659C.description:
Pretend to write in
ways that mimic adult
writing (e.g., scribble
on paper while sitting
with caregiver who is
writing, hold phone to
ear and make marks
with pencil).

B65B091E5D5E47E58E20FECCF34F16B9.description:
Make marks,
scribble, and paint
(e.g., cover easel
paper with big
crayon or paint marks,
make marks with
marker or crayon).

0373773CF314479A95C8C44DCD368A76.description:
Children use writing and other symbols to record information and communicate for a
variety of purposes.

32440D6902E941769192A0EE6653975E.description:
Associate sounds with
the letters at the beginning
of some words, such as
awareness that two words
begin with the same letter
and the same sound.

4D84E8E9968947D7B15633354FAF9534.description:
Make some sound-to-letter
matches, using letter name
knowledge (notice the letter
B with picture of ball and
say, “Ball”; say, “A-a-apple.”).

9BEBC269628A438A995F3252780DD5B6.description:
Recognize and name
many letters of the alphabet,
especially those in their own
name and in the names of
others who are important to
them.

F76AE9F45D6F43C38AD3063C5DFF2504.description:
Show they know that letters
function to represent sounds
in spoken words.

E8D1D856F5444877A3733C6AA941D19A.description: Demonstrate an interest in learning the alphabet.

8C5C5849C38D45C5A3A623610340FE11.description:
Recognize and name
some letters of the
alphabet, especially
those in their own
name.

50F2B99BA01A425494A8BDCD0824F190.description:
Recognize letters
of the alphabet as a
special category of
print, different from
pictures, shapes, and
numerals.

4C4AD8E75C4141EC842DFF9F0E22FEB1.description: Demonstrate an interest in learning the alphabet.

91AE638B9F9D46C4BB0D0321A3DFC598.description:
Demonstrate an
interest in letters by
asking about and/or
naming some of them.

D1E006B65874472D93339DF3E2EE0697.description: Children begin to develop knowledge of the alphabet and the alphabetic principle.

F8C5721ED16D48DDA9C0BD5532191A9F.description:
Associate sounds with
specific words, such as
awareness that different
words begin with the same
sound.

38123E0FE1294D68B5E16C9B8094D3B9.description:
Play with the sounds of
language, identify a variety
of rhymes, create some
rhymes, and recognize the
first sounds in some words.

C7376DBB2FC74943BC2CA377F08065AA.description:
Repeat a variety of
rhythmic patterns in poems
and songs using words,
clapping, marching, and/
or instruments to repeat the
rhythm or beat syllables.

F2A461C589F344BA8D1DF2D8BDF27C5C.description:
Enjoy rhymes and wordplay
with songs, poems, and
books and sometimes add
their own variations.

1B84F0684BCE463D8F3C080F0A6AC83B.description:
Distinguish between similar
sounding words (e.g. tree
and three).

9966C8B667C641C3BBA459009A009E76.description:
Play with the
sounds of language
and begin to identify
rhymes (make up
silly-sounding words,
repeat rhyming
words).

9D08FC17888B4926B56DE51BA549CE70.description:
Repeat rhythmic
patterns in poems and
songs using words,
clapping, marching,
and/or using
instruments.

E54193980B734298BFFEE11CF7BA3A6F.description:
Participate in
experiences with
songs, poems, and
books that have
rhyme and wordplay,
and learn words well
enough to complete
refrains and fill in
missing words and
sounds.

75CA3AF5BE404581894ACB857B476CAD.description:
Participate in
experiences using
rhythmic patterns
in poems and songs
using words, clapping,
marching, and/or using
instruments.

2E48E5F66EC6416CB5D04E748B970E12.description:
Notice sounds that
are the same and
different.

7F7EB282D264413A9D99098FD3B1394F.description:
Focus on and enjoy
playing with repetitive
sounds, words,
rhymes, and gestures.

EC0AFBC13C8747568CF4D278B6D9118C.description:
Imitate and
take turns with
caregivers making
different sounds.

72C64EC43C0C4D48A96EF492EEA6098F.description:
Discuss storybooks by responding
to questions about the beginning,
middle, and end of the story.

704609CBCDBD454C83CF2311F60552CA.description:
Discuss storybooks by responding
to questions about what is
happening and predicting what will
happen next.

FB58940193F34EB1920ACABEF01A5AB7.description:
Ask more focused and detailed
questions about a story or the
information in a book.

A97C280DA030472BA5E0511E9AA17094.description:
Relate personal experiences to
an increasing variety of events
described in familiar and new
books.

EBE0AE7F2A5F4286A3C830097745DB69.description:
Use knowledge of the world to
make sense of more challenging
texts.

CD25093DEA7D426FA9D6EE5A81DA5829.description:
Use informational texts and
other media to learn about the
world, and infer from illustrations,
ask questions and talk about the
information.

20F511A571614F59BF932AE227BAF63D.description:
Imitate the special language in
storybooks and story dialogue with
accuracy and detail.

D21F0C99AA50406F80C2B6CB216DCB2F.description:
With prompting and support,
discuss storybooks by responding
to questions about what is
happening and predicting what will
happen next.

07D299D26FE54597B34E4518BD0DEB0F.description:
Ask questions about a story or
the information in a book.

40601233CD4242CFA0E1E4508391E875.description:
Relate personal experiences to
events described in familiar books,
with prompting and support.

B1C433890A0C481AB39ECDFCF466FE79.description:
Use their knowledge of the world
(what things are, how things work)
to make sense of stories and
informational texts.

B1F80EFCA201435B8079D09C11282A03.description:
With prompting and support,
use books and other media that
communicate information to learn
about the world by looking at
pictures, asking questions, and
talking about the information.

6A015A29B27748ACADC19DA0F53D574B.description:
Imitate the special language in
storybooks and story dialogue with
some accuracy and detail.

D71BE46DC24B46E9BFFC6538B3077656.description:
Imitate the special
language in storybooks
and story dialogue
(repetitive language
patterns, sound effects,
and words from familiar
stories).

2AEFDA9713D84F549727E9A468CB1D87.description:
Begin to relate personal
experiences to events
described in familiar
books.

CD1AB192DFA046D39D6BAD2A86CC334B.description:
Pretend to read familiar
books from memory;
repeat familiar phrases
while looking at a book.

28C214ED32EB4D43AAC5CE7279111961.description:
Chime in on a repeated
line in a book while being
read to by an adult.

F16C708630554764B242E376B55C10A4.description:
Make appropriate
sounds when looking at
pictures (say, “Quack,
quack” when looking
at a duck, “Vrrrrooom”
when looking at a car).

4A4621202249434D8AB6E540E182BB59.description:
Allow entire short
book to be “read” with
willingness to look at
most pages.

62FB5FB74D2B439481664BE1B53E1804.description:
Listen to and repeat
parts of simple and
repetitive books, stories,
songs, and finger plays.

E9F6CA963747488AAB0FF75AE1E0881D.description: Children comprehend and use information presented in books and other print media.

5A55CE63EF1541BCB46A0650627272D8.description:
Identify their name and the names
of some friends when they see them
in print.

8DDF384F036040559F7A9D565F1A1A35.description:
Demonstrate an understanding
of some basic print conventions
(the concept of what a letter is, the
concept of words, directionality of
print).

45BB927549194EC9AFD0DFC5A3385A70.description:
With prompting and support, run
their finger under or over print as
they pretend to read text.

4C8B5C8458964A00B2B6DFBE3C86DEA8.description:
Recognize print and symbols used
to organize classroom activities
and show understanding of their
meaning (put toys in box with
correct symbol and name; check
sign-up sheet for popular activity;
check schedule to learn next
activity).

C8BB1CFF49354FD6B6E723F5547AB3ED.description:
Recognize print in different forms
for a variety of functions (writing a
message to friend, pointing to print
and saying, “Those words tell the
story,” or reading familiar signs in
the environment).

F4CF8D28B4FF4D7BB8D660730E72C9B4.description:
Hold a book upright while turning
pages one by one from front to
back.

5D4EB02488664DB4A5DAB6A5C37D0A79.description:
Demonstrate an
understanding that
print and symbols can
tell people what to do
(to organize classroom
activities—where to store
things, when they will
have a turn).

CBF6C65FFD1146048E241E5D6A29F693.description:
With prompting and
support, recognize print
occurs in different forms
and is used for a variety
of functions (sign naming
block structure, “message”
on card for family
member).

D939EE0B566D4B7EB500BF2312E6534D.description:
Hold a book upright
while turning pages one
by one front to back, but
not always in order.

771A03CF2DD647D99560A8C2906EABEC.description:
Demonstrate an
understanding of
realistic symbols such as
photographs, and later,
abstract symbols such as
signs and environmental
print (know which pictures
stand for which activities
on a daily schedule; say,
“That means light” when
looking at a symbol of a
light bulb located over the
light switch).

45A140419791480EB188F674EE3E2B54.description:
Demonstrate
understanding of the
need for and the uses of
print (pretend to read a
“grocery list” during play;
say, “I want chicken” when
looking at a menu).

041A7E71EF8E46E18946579524403C16.description:
Hold a book upright, turn
some pages front to back
(but not always in the right
order), close book, and
say, “done” or “the end.”

CC0858CD2F094C708429B8CD4F4A2FE4.description:
Identify some
environmental print and
logos (favorite cereal
box, a sign for a familiar
store).

6FE94CE26E844A36A760AD85AC9087F2.description:
Turn pages (but not
always in the right
order); point to and
label pictures in books;
sometimes treat
pictures as real (licking
a picture of ice cream,
rubbing “fur” of a cat in
a book).

03E6F94670E94736BAD8A190E706026A.description:
Look at pictures
while cuddling
with caregiver.

4000649F85AF48118CDC900B54C33EFF.description:
Explore books
and paper by tasting,
mouthing, crumpling,
banging, and
patting.

57BAEDA9372949D6B92A59C0BE41577F.description: Children develop book knowledge and print awareness.

7FA58E2D5CCD4EA5AC2E8C86E01A90D0.description:
Listen to and
discuss increasingly
complex storybooks,
information books, and
poetry.

0B3E810055834B01BD21741C2B321955.description:
Use and share books
and print in their play.

0D00905E98DF464FB8178CFF393FBF8D.description:
Engage in
reading behaviors
independently with
increased focus for
longer periods of time.

F8356A976F014BE5A74131E864EE3E13.description:
Listen to and discuss
storybooks, simple
information books,
and poetry.

CFA0DA8AC6A147158DFA798A73C18BA2.description:
Show an interest
in books, other print,
and reading related
activities.

81C8C32FD48A45E9816F338101FD5354.description:
Engage in reading
behaviors
independently
(choose books, turn
pages but not always
in order, tell the story).

1C85D43EBCC94DC498A880A15A7C6211.description:
Listen for short
periods of time to
storybooks,
informational books,
stories, poetry, songs,
and finger plays.

4090CC11AAB64A18A7E778E03B7B8B51.description:
Engage in reading
behaviors
independently
(choose books, turn
 pages but not always
in order, tell the story).

E8E47E6F99CB47219E6DD6753D2BD9A4.description:
Carry books around,
“name” them, and
select books for
adults to read out
loud.

7C689069AB6642CDBE9CAB626B8B59D0.description:
Listen to simple
and repetitive books,
stories, and songs for
a brief time.

7FB6A06889744ED8A4691456D36E0923.description:
Show interest in
books (e.g., tactile
and picture books).

2563DB5938EA44A8BBAB16598A834485.description:
Engage in
reading behaviors
independently
(choose books, turn
pages but not always
in order, tell the
story).

A685136641F142AE852C279CB59B549F.description:
Listen to simple and
repetitive books,
stories, and songs.

5E5C376529EC4698A0856342AC0A0F8D.description:
Look at pictures of
faces and simple
objects.

38A574D75E394EE0A5166654655BADB1.description:
Pat and chew on
tactile books.

22DF495FA68E4926AB6DD521844DD8F5.description: Children develop interest in books and motivation to read.

7C1B007885814937BE31937789C300C2.description:
Distinguish between
real and made up
words.

55BAA2403E4B449AA112E3CF0BDDD57A.description:
Infer the meaning of
different kinds of new
words from the context
in which they are used
(for example, hear
“sandals” and “boots”
used to describe two
pairs of shoes, and
infer that the unfamiliar
shoes must be sandals
because they know that
the other pair of shoes
are boots).

48ACB00665554866834FD265D3DBD9EF.description:
Use a growing
vocabulary that
includes many kinds of
words to express ideas
clearly.

F3E670AD98BC4305942564D9AE8A039E.description:
Repeat familiar
songs, chants, or
rhymes.

5B0C1692DC6941FC92C6518A7151711D.description:
Use many kinds
of cues in the
environment to figure
out what words mean.

572C040B954541269932CBE21FB3BD40.description:
Make up names
for things using
words they know
(e.g., dog doctor for
veterinarian).

BB8FA6397AF34966BC7C15BFA48FFCFB.description:
Use more than one
word for the same
object and use words
for parts of objects
(e.g., dog, beagle,
Rover; arm, leg).

DDC8CF81C26B46EEA55C26C129F7323D.description:
Repeat familiar
songs, chants, or
rhymes.

08ECE823BBA34F24964A2D11F82B8DF0.description:
Use proper nouns
for people and things.

EDF7C39DC85547FA9C8C6313A098586B.description:
Show they
understand many new
vocabulary words and
a variety of concepts
(big and little, in and
out).

4CA865FD2C5C4B679F6F601972A87AE6.description:
Participate in or
repeat familiar songs,
chants, or rhymes.

229141C8AF3F46E3BF7FFBDF91CB14B2.description:
Use new words each
day and have a word
for almost all familiar
people, objects,
actions, and conditions
(hot, rainy, sleepy).

297EB2C946194732BCD266191A957160.description:
Use several words
to make requests
(e.g., “done,” “wannit,”
“please”) as well as to
label people and
objects.

8E6FA8D6DFE148B4BCC17B1F68A8FC5E.description:
Respond to simple
words and phrases
that they hear often.

18B71F77BCBA4005A783F3613B461324.description:
Imitate parts of
familiar songs,
chants, or rhymes.

EEBC83E9FECA40159CBCDA13F7C4F970.description:
Show steady
increase in words
used (e.g., name
family members and
familiar objects).

51D97883179D4AC9A9FC80DE87150783.description:
Recognize spoken
or signed words for
common items.

1B4D925F2DFD4A618F9E29769571BD94.description:
Make specific
sounds, facial
expressions, and/or
gestures for certain
people and objects.

334564544DAC49E78F3B8360EB6E7BA1.description: Children respond to and use a growing vocabulary.

D8CC4F493562407E9BD31A47FC7AD5E2.description:
Speak in full
sentences that are
grammatically correct
most of the time.

386C3313AB5D47E08CA98CDAD298C978.description:
Make grammatical
errors that follow
language rules (say,
“mouses” instead of
“mice”).

46B00E0790CE4838A9F99A193F5A825D.description:
Communicate in
longer sentences
and use more
conventional
grammar in their
home language
(plurals, tenses,
prepositions).

4544B4EFEFF540E8841862CAD3301FCA.description:
Communicate in short
sentences that follow
the word order of their
home language.

5993F7FD097046C786C75783BAB0A600.description:
Use a few words to
communicate (make
requests and ask
questions).

C3E3B5DBEBFE431381C968B6518A7369.description:
“Jabber” and put
together vocalizations
in a way that sounds
similar to the rhythm
and flow of their home
language.

4B862CDEA2C14822B266CDA0627A49EB.description:
“Jabber” and pretend
to talk using many
sounds or signs
from the languages
used around them to
communicate.

4BBA5DD4700D40E49259C3DDE9A38572.description:
Make different
sounds for different
purposes (whimper
when wet, cry loudly
when hungry).

D41CB622437C4D89AC2F93046F4DEF13.description: Children use most grammatical constructions of their home language well.

6853DDB1609B4560A43E8438C097A354.description:
Describe experiences
and create and/or
retell longer narratives.

8C1090AC61A54051970A27CE8B9D6B18.description:
Describe
experiences and
create or retell short
narratives.

55B69184963544EDB8D3A04EEBA323A5.description:
Talk to themselves
and others about what they are “working on,” what they are doing, routines, and events
of the day.

68AEF76924A74AFDB301FBDEB2295B5C.description:
Use dramatic play to
act out familiar scenes
and events and imitate
familiar people.

66348E5450A84A5EA88709F5BDF1F70D.description:
Talk to themselves
and others about what they are “working on,” what they are doing, routines, and events of
the day.

57FED074A34842EBAF35C9C8DA726D62.description:
Act out familiar
scenes and events,
and imitate familiar
people.

1D048FA8AB874BE7BEBD9E7AAB47BB95.description: Children describe familiar people, places, things, and events.

9FB6DE0C9211473186FB22B097D9946B.description:
Express ideas in more
than one way.

444EE00188A742CC819D009BA3ACB6B0.description:
State point of view, likes
and dislikes.

CAC888635908425F8B9BBA7C1082B11C.description:
Speak clearly enough
to be understood by most
people.

B4A679DD5CB141469FAF0C995E646035.description:
Adapt their
communication to meet
social expectations
(speak quietly in library,
speak politely to older
relative).

5058991155F94A8E912795CFA51ABF3D.description:
Use language and
nonverbal cues to
communicate thoughts,
beliefs, feelings, and
intentions.

9DBC4C54A8644BC3B905477B3A14CA2D.description:
Speak clearly enough to be understood by familiar
adults and children.

B9DA57EE36FE4BF899ECBD99330DBA85.description:
Communicate messages with expression, tone, and inflection appropriate
to the situation.

9B5880B26BA746549C1A8BF8BA6E8330.description:
Use speech that is understood most of the
time by familiar listeners.

CD7ADEB617B945C782C337EEB9349B5A.description: Communicate messages with expression, tone, and inflection.

0D1BC699901446149AB22A3267FB066A.description:
Use non-verbal
gestures to express
ideas and feelings.

4C9998C922E8452C8143ED90563BFDCF.description:
Expect others to
understand them and
show frustration, often
through their
behavior, if not
understood.

5BD46F6181E941F486368BED95F15509.description:
Communicate
through facial
expressions, sounds,
and body movements.
